# sources/ — references and prior art

The articles, forum threads, datasheets, documentation, and tools this
investigation draws on. The investigation stands on this prior work; record it
so a finding can be traced back to its basis and so a thread can be re-found when
a verbatim error string needs searching.

## What to record per source

Keep a notes file (or a row in an index) per source with:

- **Title / identifier** and **URL** (or where it lives if offline).
- **Date accessed** (absolute).
- **Why it matters** — the specific thing this source contributes (the worked
  example, the part number, the procedure step).
- **Reliability** — primary/authoritative vs. forum-anecdote. Note when a claim
  is unverified.
- Optionally, a **cached copy** (if the source is fragile/likely to vanish and
  the artifact policy permits storing it).

## Suggested layout

```
sources/
  README.md
  INDEX.md            (one row per source: id, title, url, why-it-matters, reliability)
  <slug>.md           (notes on a specific source)
  cache/              (optional offline copies, if policy permits)
```

## Discipline

- **Cite, don't launder.** When a fact in the docs comes from a source, link the
  source — especially for anything risky or surprising.
- **Mark anecdotes as anecdotes.** A single forum post is a lead, not a fact,
  until corroborated. Note the difference.
- **Verify against primary sources** where a wrong fact would cost time, money,
  or the subject. Prefer official docs/datasheets over secondary blogs.
